hands_on_practices.introduction:
A common point of confusion when studying black-body radiation is the distinction between the peak of the spectrum when plotted against wavelength versus frequency. Because the relationship between spectral density in wavelength, $u_{\lambda}$, and in frequency, $u_{
u}$, is non-linear (specifically, $|u_{\lambda} d\lambda| = |u_{
u} d
u|$), their peaks do not coincide. This advanced problem guides you through the calculus to find the locations of both peaks and compute their ratio, offering a deeper insight into the mathematical structure of Planck's law and the importance of the transformation between dependent variables [@problem_id:1843645].
